<!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════
     PAGE 1 — MEDICAL USE CASE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="page-usecase" class="page active">

  <h1>Knowledge graph — hospital drug safety</h1>
  <p style="margin-top:.5rem; font-size:15px;">One use case, four concepts. Dr. Smith wants to prescribe Aspirin to Patient John. John is already on Warfarin. Watch every layer activate.</p>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- THE PROBLEM -->
  <h2>The problem — data without connection</h2>
  <p>A hospital has three systems. None of them talk to each other. A doctor must check all three manually before every prescription — and still might miss a dangerous interaction.</p>

  <div class="vs-grid">
    <div class="card card-sm alert-danger" style="border:none;">
      <div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:.5rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.04em;">Without knowledge graph</div>
      <div style="font-size:13px;line-height:1.8;">
        ✗ 3 separate systems, no connection<br>
        ✗ Manual lookup — 20 minutes<br>
        ✗ Easy to miss drug interactions<br>
        ✗ No automatic alert<br>
        ✗ Patient history fragmented
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card card-sm alert-success" style="border:none;">
      <div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:700;margin-bottom:.5rem;text-transform:uppercase;letter-spacing:.04em;">With knowledge graph</div>
      <div style="font-size:13px;line-height:1.8;">
        ✓ One connected graph<br>
        ✓ Answer in under 1 second<br>
        ✓ Interactions flagged automatically<br>
        ✓ OWL rule fires, alert raised<br>
        ✓ Complete picture, one query
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- RDF -->
  <h2><span class="pill tag-rdf">RDF</span> &nbsp;Every fact is a triple</h2>
  <p>Resource Description Framework. Every single fact is written as exactly three parts: Subject → Predicate → Object. No exceptions.</p>

  <div class="alert alert-info">Think of it like short sentences with exactly three words. "Patient → takes → Aspirin." That is one triple. Every fact in the hospital becomes one of these.</div>

  <h3>John's medical facts — written as triples</h3>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="triple-row"><span class="t-s">Patient_John</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-p">takesMedication</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-o">Warfarin</span><span class="t-note">← John is on Warfarin</span></div>
    <div class="triple-row"><span class="t-s">Patient_John</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-p">takesMedication</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-o">Aspirin</span><span class="t-note">← also on Aspirin</span></div>
    <div class="triple-row"><span class="t-s">Warfarin</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-p">interactsWith</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-o">Aspirin</span><span class="t-note">← dangerous combination</span></div>
    <div class="triple-row"><span class="t-s">Patient_John</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-p">treatedBy</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-o">Dr_Smith</span><span class="t-note">← his physician</span></div>
    <div class="triple-row"><span class="t-s">Patient_John</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-p">hasAllergy</span><span class="t-arr">→</span><span class="t-o">Penicillin</span><span class="t-note">← allergy on record</span></div>
  </div>

<pre><span class="cm"># Turtle format — how you write RDF</span>
<span class="cm">@prefix : &lt;http://hospital.org/&gt; .</span>

<span class="va">:Patient_John</span>  <span class="kw">a</span>                    <span class="st">:Patient</span> ;
               <span class="kw">:takesMedication</span>     <span class="st">:Warfarin</span> ;
               <span class="kw">:takesMedication</span>     <span class="st">:Aspirin</span> ;
               <span class="kw">:treatedBy</span>           <span class="st">:Dr_Smith</span> ;
               <span class="kw">:hasAllergy</span>          <span class="st">:Penicillin</span> .

<span class="va">:Warfarin</span>      <span class="kw">:interactsWith</span>       <span class="st">:Aspirin</span> .</pre>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- ONTOLOGY -->
  <h2><span class="pill tag-onto">Ontology</span> &nbsp;Defining what things ARE</h2>
  <p>An ontology is the rulebook for your domain. It defines what kinds of things exist, what properties they can have, and what relationships are allowed.</p>

  <div class="alert alert-warn">Think of it as a medical dictionary combined with a rulebook. "Aspirin IS a Drug. Drug IS a Substance. A Drug CAN interact-with another Drug." Define it once — every fact in the graph inherits the rules.</div>

  <h3>Hospital class hierarchy</h3>
  <div class="card">
    <div class="hier-row"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:var(--blue-bg);color:var(--blue-dk);">MedicalEntity — everything in the hospital</div></div>
    <div class="hier-indent">
      <div class="hier-row"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:var(--green-bg);color:var(--green-dk);">Person — has name, DOB, ID</div></div>
      <div class="hier-indent">
        <div class="hier-row"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:#f0faf5;color:#085041;">Patient — has conditions, medications, doctors</div></div>
        <div class="hier-row"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:#f0faf5;color:#085041;">Doctor — has specialty, license, patients</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="hier-row" style="margin-top:6px;"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:var(--amber-bg);color:var(--amber-dk);">Substance — has dosage, composition</div></div>
      <div class="hier-indent">
        <div class="hier-row"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:#fdf3e0;color:#633806;">Drug — has interactions, contraindications</div></div>
        <div class="hier-row"><div class="hier-chip" style="background:#fdf3e0;color:#633806;">Allergy — has severity, trigger</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

<pre><span class="cm"># RDFS / OWL ontology</span>
<span class="va">:Patient</span>   <span class="kw">rdfs:subClassOf</span>  <span class="st">:Person</span> .
<span class="va">:Drug</span>      <span class="kw">rdfs:subClassOf</span>  <span class="st">:Substance</span> .

<span class="cm"># interactsWith goes both ways</span>
<span class="va">:interactsWith</span>  <span class="kw">a</span>              <span class="st">owl:SymmetricProperty</span> ;
                <span class="kw">rdfs:domain</span>   <span class="st">:Drug</span> ;
                <span class="kw">rdfs:range</span>    <span class="st">:Drug</span> .

<span class="cm"># A patient has exactly one blood type</span>
<span class="va">:bloodType</span>  <span class="kw">a</span>  <span class="st">owl:FunctionalProperty</span> .</pre>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- OWL -->
  <h2><span class="pill tag-owl">OWL</span> &nbsp;Rules that think for you</h2>
  <p>OWL adds logic to your ontology. You write IF/THEN rules. A reasoner applies them automatically to every patient, every drug, every relationship — and generates conclusions you never explicitly stored.</p>

  <div class="alert alert-danger">Think of OWL rules like a senior doctor's standing orders: "IF a patient is taking Drug A AND Drug A interacts with Drug B AND a doctor prescribes Drug B → block the prescription and raise an alert." Write it once. It runs on every patient, forever.</div>

  <h3>Three rules for the hospital</h3>
  <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;margin-bottom:.4rem;">
      <span style="font-size:13px;font-weight:600;">Drug interaction alert</span>
      <span class="pill" style="background:var(--red-bg);color:var(--red-dk);">Fires for John</span>
    </div>
    <div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.6;">IF patient takes Drug A + Drug A interacts-with Drug B + doctor prescribes Drug B<br><strong style="color:var(--red);">THEN raise DANGER alert → block prescription</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="card" style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">
    <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;margin-bottom:.4rem;">
      <span style="font-size:13px;font-weight:600;">High-risk patient flag</span>
      <span class="pill" style="background:var(--border);color:var(--muted);">Does not fire</span>
    </div>
    <div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.6;">IF patient has more than 5 medications + age &gt; 70<br><strong style="color:var(--green);">THEN classify as HighRiskPatient → require pharmacist review</strong></div>
  </div>
  <div class="card">
    <div style="display:flex;justify-content:space-between;align-items:center;margin-bottom:.4rem;">
      <span style="font-size:13px;font-weight:600;">Allergy cross-check</span>
      <span class="pill" style="background:var(--red-bg);color:var(--red-dk);">Fires for John</span>
    </div>
    <div style="font-size:12px;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.6;">IF patient has allergy to Penicillin + doctor prescribes Amoxicillin (same family)<br><strong style="color:var(--amber);">THEN raise WARNING → Amoxicillin is a penicillin-type drug</strong></div>
  </div>

<pre><span class="cm"># SWRL-style rule — drug interaction check</span>
<span class="kw">IF</span>   <span class="va">?patient</span>  <span class="st">:takesMedication</span>  <span class="va">?drugA</span>
     <span class="va">?drugA</span>    <span class="st">:interactsWith</span>    <span class="va">?drugB</span>
     <span class="va">?doctor</span>   <span class="st">:prescribes</span>       <span class="va">?drugB</span>
     <span class="va">?doctor</span>   <span class="st">:treatedBy</span>        <span class="va">?patient</span>
<span class="kw">THEN</span> CREATE <span class="st">:Alert</span>
         <span class="st">:severity</span>   <span class="st">"DANGER"</span>
         <span class="st">:message</span>    <span class="st">"Drug interaction detected"</span>
         <span class="st">:blocked</span>    <span class="va">?drugB</span></pre>

  <hr class="divider">

  <!-- SPARQL -->
  <h2><span class="pill tag-sparql">SPARQL</span> &nbsp;Asking the graph questions</h2>
  <p>SPARQL is the query language for knowledge graphs. You describe the shape of the answer you want — the graph finds everything that matches.</p>

  <div class="card card-sm" style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">
    <div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:600;color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:.35rem;">Query 1 — find dangerous combinations for John</div>
<pre style="margin:0;">SELECT <span class="va">?drug ?interaction</span> WHERE {
  <span class="st">:Patient_John</span>  <span class="kw">:takesMedication</span>  <span class="va">?drug</span> .
  <span class="va">?drug</span>          <span class="kw">:interactsWith</span>    <span class="va">?interaction</span> .
}</pre>
    <div class="alert alert-success" style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Result: Warfarin ↔ Aspirin (interaction detected)</div>
  </div>

  <div class="card card-sm" style="margin-bottom:.5rem;">
    <div style="font-size:12px;font-weight:600;color:var(--muted);margin-bottom:.35rem;">Query 2 — find John's treating doctors</div>
<pre style="margin:0;">SELECT <span class="va">?doctor ?specialty</span> WHERE {
  <span class="st">:Patient_John</span>  <span class="kw">:treatedBy</span>       <span class="va">?doctor</span> .
  <span class="va">?doctor</span>        <span class="kw">:hasSpecialty</span>    <span class="va">?specialty</span> .
}</pre>
    <div class="alert alert-success" style="margin:.5rem 0 0;">Result: Dr. Smith (Cardiology)</div>
  </div>

