              detail:"A named graph is a set of triples with its own URI. GRAPH :LabSystem { :Patient_John :hasBiomarker :Troponin } GRAPH :EHRSystem { :Patient_John :age '38' } Now query: 'which system does this fact come from?' or 'show me only facts from the lab system'. Essential for audit trails, trust levels, and regulatory compliance." },
            { id:"a-in-4", title:"SPARQL federation — querying across multiple endpoints",
              detail:"SERVICE keyword queries a remote endpoint inside your own query. SELECT ?drug ?trial WHERE { :Patient_John :takesMedication ?drug . SERVICE <http://clinicaltrials.gov/sparql> { ?trial :studyDrug ?drug } } Your local graph joins with an external clinical trials database in one query. No ETL pipeline needed — the data stays in its source system." },
          ]
        },
        {
          title: "Industrial IoT — mapping to oil and manufacturing",
          tag: "concept",
          topics: [
            { id:"a-iot-1", title:"Transfer: Patient → Equipment, Drug → Component",
              detail:"Every concept transfers directly. Patient → Equipment. Drug → Component or process fluid. Drug interaction → part incompatibility or chemical reaction risk. Doctor → Maintenance engineer. Prescription alert → Maintenance work order. OWL rule → sensor threshold rule. The exact same RDF + Ontology + OWL pattern works in both domains." },
            { id:"a-iot-2", title:"SSN/SOSA — the W3C sensor ontology",
              detail:"W3C SSN (Semantic Sensor Network) / SOSA ontology defines how sensors work. sosa:Sensor (your IoT device), sosa:Observation (each reading), sosa:hasSimpleResult (the value), sosa:observedProperty (what it measures). Your temperature sensor: :Sensor_T01 a sosa:Sensor ; sosa:observes :Temperature_PipelineA3 . Each reading becomes a structured, queryable triple." },
            { id:"a-iot-3", title:"ISO 15926 — the oil and gas standard ontology",
              detail:"ISO 15926 is the RDF ontology standard for oil and gas equipment and processes. Every pump, valve, sensor, pipeline section, and maintenance event has a standardised class. Start here instead of designing from scratch. Using ISO 15926 means your graph speaks the same language as every other oil company using the standard — and satisfies regulatory data requirements." },
            { id:"a-iot-4", title:"Equipment hierarchy — plant, unit, system, component",
              detail:"Model your asset hierarchy: Plant → Unit → System → Equipment → Component. Use :isPartOf for instance hierarchy. Use rdfs:subClassOf for type hierarchy. Then: if a Component fails, traverse :isPartOf upward to find the affected Unit. If a Unit is critical, traverse downward to find all Components needing inspection. OWL rule: IF Component hasStatus :Failed AND Component isPartOf Unit THEN Unit hasStatus :Impacted." },
            { id:"a-iot-5", title:"FMEA as OWL — failure mode encoding",
              detail:"FMEA (Failure Mode and Effects Analysis) maps perfectly to OWL. :FailureMode class with properties :affectsComponent, :detectedBy (links to Sensor), :severity. OWL rule: IF Sensor reads above threshold AND Sensor :detects FailureMode AND FailureMode :affects Component THEN Component hasStatus :AtRisk. This is the drug interaction rule in industrial form." },
          ]
        },
        {
          title: "Demo — ready to present",
          tag: "demo",
          topics: [
            { id:"a-dm-1", title:"Minimum viable demo — what you need",
              detail:"You need exactly: one Turtle file (10–20 triples), one OWL ontology file (3–5 classes, 2 rules), one SPARQL query that shows inference. Load both in GraphDB or Protégé. Run the reasoner. Run the query. Show the result. Total demo time: 5 minutes. That is enough to prove the concept completely to any technical audience." },
            { id:"a-dm-2", title:"The five-step narrative arc",
              detail:"1) Show the raw data problem (numbers with no context). 2) Add RDF — now numbers have connected meaning. 3) Add ontology — now context has rules. 4) Fire OWL reasoner — now the system infers. 5) Run SPARQL — now you can ask questions across the whole graph. This arc IS your demo script, your slide structure, and your explanation framework." },
            { id:"a-dm-3", title:"Protégé walkthrough — a 3-minute script",
              detail:"Open Protégé (30s). Show class hierarchy (30s). Show two instances with properties (30s). Start HermiT reasoner — watch inferred classes appear (30s). Open SPARQL tab, run the interaction query (30s). Show result (30s). Total: 3 minutes. Practise until it is smooth and automatic. The demo should feel like you are showing off something that just works, not explaining how it works." },
            { id:"a-dm-4", title:"Three questions an architect will ask — and how to answer",
              detail:"Q1: 'How does this scale to millions of sensors?' — Graph databases like Stardog, AWS Neptune, and GraphDB Enterprise handle billions of triples. The same Turtle and OWL files work at any scale. Q2: 'How does new data get in?' — R2RML mappings or Kafka pipelines convert streaming data to triples automatically. Q3: 'How is this different from a database?' — A database stores data. This stores meaning and reasons across it automatically." },
            { id:"a-dm-5", title:"The one diagram that explains everything",
              detail:"Draw this on one slide: three circles labelled Patient_John, Warfarin, Aspirin. Arrows between them: takesMedication, interactsWith. One box labelled 'OWL rule: IF interaction exists THEN alert'. One arrow from the box labelled 'INFERRED: Alert generated'. That diagram IS the knowledge graph. Everything else in your presentation is just supporting detail for this one picture." },
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  };

  // Storage
  function getChecked() {
    try { return JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem('kg_checked') || '{}'); } catch(e) { return {}; }
  }
  function saveChecked(obj) {
    try { localStorage.setItem('kg_checked', JSON.stringify(obj)); } catch(e) {}
  }

  let checked = getChecked();
  let activeLevel = 'beginner';
  let openSections = {};
  let expandedTopics = {};

  function totalFor(level) {
    return TOPICS[level].sections.reduce((s, sec) => s + sec.topics.length, 0);
  }
  function doneFor(level) {
    return TOPICS[level].sections.reduce((s, sec) =>
      s + sec.topics.filter(t => checked[t.id]).length, 0);
  }
  function pct(level) {
    const t = totalFor(level);
    return t ? Math.round(doneFor(level) / t * 100) : 0;
  }

  function renderLevelTabs() {
    const el = document.getElementById('level-tabs');
    el.innerHTML = Object.keys(TOPICS).map(key => {
      const L = TOPICS[key];
      const p = pct(key);
      return `<button class="level-tab${key===activeLevel?' active':''}" onclick="setLevel('${key}')">
        <div class="lt-label">${L.label}</div>
        <div class="lt-sub">${L.sub} · ${L.weeks}</div>
        <div class="lt-prog"><div class="lt-fill" style="width:${p}%;background:${L.color}"></div></div>
      </button>`;
    }).join('');
  }

  function renderProgress() {
    const L = TOPICS[activeLevel];
    const done = doneFor(activeLevel);
    const total = totalFor(activeLevel);
    const p = pct(activeLevel);
    document.getElementById('progress-area').innerHTML = `
      <div class="progress-summary"><strong>${done} of ${total}</strong> topics completed — ${p}%</div>
      <div class="progress-bar-lg"><div class="fill" style="width:${p}%;background:${L.color}"></div></div>
      <div class="alert" style="background:${L.color}18;color:${L.color};border-left:3px solid ${L.color};margin-bottom:1rem;">
        <strong>Goal:</strong> ${L.goal}
      </div>`;
  }

  function tagClass(tag) {
    return { rdf:'tag-rdf', owl:'tag-owl', onto:'tag-onto', sparql:'tag-sparql', demo:'tag-demo', concept:'tag-concept' }[tag] || 'tag-concept';
  }

  function renderChecklist() {
    const L = TOPICS[activeLevel];
    const el = document.getElementById('checklist-content');
    el.innerHTML = L.sections.map((sec, si) => {
      const secDone = sec.topics.filter(t => checked[t.id]).length;
      const isOpen = openSections[`${activeLevel}-${si}`] !== false; // default open
      return `<div class="section-block">
        <div class="section-head${isOpen?' open':''}" onclick="toggleSection('${activeLevel}-${si}', ${si})">
          <span class="pill ${tagClass(sec.tag)}">${sec.tag}</span>
          <span class="sh-title">${sec.title}</span>
          <span class="sh-count">${secDone}/${sec.topics.length}</span>
          <span class="sh-chevron">▶</span>
        </div>
        ${isOpen ? `<div class="section-items">
          ${sec.topics.map((t, ti) => {
            const isChecked = !!checked[t.id];
            const isExpanded = !!expandedTopics[t.id];
            return `<div class="topic-row${isExpanded?' expanded':''}" onclick="toggleTopic('${t.id}', ${si}, ${ti})">
              <div class="topic-check${isChecked?' checked':''}" onclick="event.stopPropagation();toggleCheck('${t.id}')">
                <svg width="10" height="8" viewBox="0 0 10 8" fill="none"><path d="M1 4l2.5 2.5L9 1" stroke="white" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>
              <div class="topic-body">
                <div class="topic-title${isChecked?' checked':''}">${t.title}</div>
                <div class="topic-detail">${t.detail}</div>
              </div>
              <div class="topic-tag"><span style="font-size:11px;color:var(--faint)">${isExpanded?'▲':'▼'}</span></div>
            </div>`;
          }).join('')}
        </div>` : ''}
      </div>`;
    }).join('');
  }

  function render() {
    renderLevelTabs();
    renderProgress();
    renderChecklist();
  }

  window.setLevel = function(key) { activeLevel = key; render(); };
  window.toggleSection = function(key) {
    openSections[key] = openSections[key] === false ? true : false;
    render();
  };
  window.toggleTopic = function(id) {
    expandedTopics[id] = !expandedTopics[id];
    render();
  };
  window.toggleCheck = function(id) {
    checked[id] = !checked[id];
    saveChecked(checked);
    render();
  };

  render();
  </script>

  <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:1.5rem;">
    <button class="btn" onclick="clearAll()">Reset all progress</button>
  </div>
  <script>
  window.clearAll = function() {
    if(confirm('Reset all progress? This cannot be undone.')) {
      checked = {};
      saveChecked(checked);
      render();
    }
  };
  </script>

</div><!-- /page-checklist -->

<footer>
  Knowledge Graph Learning Hub · Built with RDF, Ontology & OWL concepts · Progress saved in your browser
</footer>

<script>
function showPage(id, btn) {
  document.querySelectorAll('.page').forEach(p => p.classList.remove('active'));
  document.querySelectorAll('.nav-tab').forEach(b => b.classList.remove('active'));
  document.getElementById('page-' + id).classList.add('active');
  btn.classList.add('active');
}
</script>

</body>
</html>